;;; 55-scene.slat — Motoi Scheme Reference · Chapter 55 · library scene
;;;
;;; 5 verbs in this library. Read chapter 00-intro.slat first.

;;;
;;; ─── THE ROW RULES (summary — full doctrine in 00-intro.slat) ───
;;;
;;; Every verb in this chapter has 5 rows. Each row does ONE job. Row
;;; contamination unbalances training data. If you author or edit a verb,
;;; STAY IN LANE.
;;;
;;;   Row 1 (HOW · Composition) — the verb written well; 1/3/5 module ladder
;;;   Row 2 (WHEN · Audit)      — operator's problem + this-verb-not-a-sibling
;;;   Row 3 (WHERE ELSE · Dim)  — same shape in 3 substrates (verb/metaphor/math)
;;;   Row 4 (WHY · Proof)       — claim + runnable test + ∀-invariant
;;;   Row 5 (WITH WHAT ELSE)    — chained verbs → named emergent pattern
;;;
;;; Every row carries the three-discipline lens: :eng · :math · :cs.
;;; No philosopher names in entries (they live in 00-intro.slat).
;;; Real Motoi domains only (no card/*, shop/*, cine/*, flower/*).
;;; Every code block RUNS through ./bin/motoi (or is marked :runs "spec-only").
;;;
;;; Introspection is a first-class chapter — see 00b-introspection.slat.
;;; Before authoring, run: python3 scripts/audit-reference-rows.py
;;; Before folding, run: python3 scripts/compliance-check-runnable.py
;;;

(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Library scene — 5 verbs.")

(chapter :number "55" :library "scene" :verb-count 5 :training-eligible #t)

;; ═══ 5 verbs in library scene ═══

(verb
  :name "scene/clear"
  :library "scene"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(scene/clear) -> #t"
  :summary "Reset the world to empty: remove all entities and return #t."
  :explanation "This verb wipes the current world clean, despawning every entity (prefabs, actors, particles). It is useful for level resets, loading a new scene, or returning to a blank canvas between rounds. Calling scene/clear does not affect running animations, timers, or the visual surface itself—only the entity layer. The return value is always #t (true), confirming the operation completed."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(scene/clear)" :note "Clear all entities; world is now empty")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(begin\n  (scene/clear)\n  (scene/spawn-many 'enemy (list (list 100 100) (list 200 100))))" :note "Clear the world, then spawn two enemies at specific points")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define level-data (lambda args (list \"level-data\" args)))\n(define (reset-level level-num)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (let ((enemies (level-data level-num)))\n    (for-each (lambda (e) (scene/spawn-many (car e) (cdr e)))\n              enemies)))\n(reset-level 1)" :note "Modular reset: clear, then load enemies from level-data structure")
  )
  :caveats ("scene/clear is immediate and synchronous; there is no undo." "Running animations and particles in-flight are left untouched; only the ECS entities are despawned." "Timers and event handlers registered before the clear remain active.")
  :drawbacks ("If you need a partial clear (e.g., remove only enemies, keep the player), use world/find with a filter and entity/despawn! on each result instead." "Clearing and reloading a large scene can stall a frame; consider batching with animation/budget or spreading spawns across multiple frames.")
  :usecases ("Resetting a level when the player loses or requests a retry." "Transitioning between scenes or world states." "Testing: clearing before each test case to ensure a clean slate.")
  :related ("scene/load" "scene/grid" "scene/spawn-many" "world/reset" "world/spawn" "entity/despawn" "big-bang")
  :learn (:concept "Scene management: high-level world orchestration via Motoi's scene verbs." :prerequisites ("understanding of the world entity system" "familiarity with world/spawn or entity/despawn") :progression "Master scene/clear and scene/load together for level transitions; then explore world/snapshot and world/tape-save for save/restore patterns.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "A level-transition ghost bug: after the player advances from level 1 to level 2, enemies from level 1 are still walking around in level 2. The operator suspects that the level-load path forgot to reset the world before spawning the new level's entities. Under audit they need one clean sequence — clear, then load — that guarantees no ghosts, and the sequence has to be inspectable so the audit lane can point at the exact frame where the ghost condition was resolved."
     :program "(define (transition-to next-level)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (let ((spawned (scene/load next-level)))\n    (list 'transitioned-to next-level 'ghost-check 'clean 'spawned (length spawned))))\n(display (transition-to (list (list 'player 100 100) (list 'enemy 200 100))))\n(newline)"
     :explanation "The transition function calls scene/clear first, unconditionally, so the world is empty before scene/load places the next level's entities. The return value is a stamped ledger row: which level was transitioned to, an explicit 'ghost-check: clean' marker, and the count of entities freshly spawned. When the auditor scans the log, one row per transition shows the sequence was executed. If the ghost bug reappears in the log era, the fix location is obvious — either the transition function was not called, or entities were spawned OUTSIDE the transition-to path. The scene/clear call is the LOAD-BEARING step; it is what makes the ghost-check assertion true."
     :meta "scene/clear is the honest verb here because it is the ONLY verb that guarantees the world starts empty, and its scope is precisely the entity layer — no more, no less. A sibling like world/reset would touch a wider surface (potentially timers, camera, particles) and is heavier than the audit needs. entity/despawn on individual entities would require the operator to first enumerate every entity, giving up the guarantee if enumeration is wrong. scene/load without a prior scene/clear would leave the old entities in place — the very bug we are auditing.")
    (:eng "For the operator, the transition-to function is the ONE code path all level changes go through; a single grep proves it. Adding scene/clear inside every level-change hook is the fix; the audit's log rows confirm the fix took."
     :math "The composition (scene/clear then scene/load L) is a projection followed by an insertion: the world state after the sequence equals L regardless of the world state before. This is a LEFT-ABSORBING sequence — scene/clear absorbs prior state so scene/load's result is deterministic."
     :cs "scene/clear is a MUT-kind verb with idempotent semantics on the empty-world state: once empty, further clears change nothing observable. This idempotence is what makes the transition sequence robust against duplicate invocation."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "The shape here is RESET-TO-NEUTRAL: a single call that brings a stateful container back to a canonical empty configuration, from which any subsequent build starts on known ground. That shape is not specific to scenes."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "scene/world-entities" :code "(scene/clear)")
       (:domain "os/shell-clear-screen" :code "(define (clear-screen) (list 'terminal 'wiped))\n(clear-screen)")
       (:domain "math/identity-element-of-a-monoid" :code "(define empty-list '())\n(define (reset lst) empty-list)\n(reset '(a b c))"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is the verb in its own domain: the world's entity population becomes empty. Rung 2 is a metaphor from the terminal: 'clear' at the shell wipes the visible buffer back to a fresh empty prompt, ready for the next command. The state after 'clear' is the same regardless of the state before. Rung 3 is math: every monoid has an identity element (the empty list under append, zero under addition), and RESET is the operation that maps any element to that identity. In all three cases, the shape is 'go to the empty ground state; forget prior history for this container.'"
     :meta "The shape transfers because in every case the goal is the same: eliminate hidden state that could contaminate the next operation. Scene ghosts, terminal-buffer artifacts, and unwanted list-tail residues are the same failure mode at three scales — carried-over content from a prior context. The RESET verb removes that risk by definition, and its call site is the natural audit anchor for 'fresh start'.")
    (:eng "Operators recognize the shape everywhere they have felt burned by residual state: log files not rotated, buffers not flushed, entities not despawned. The universal fix is a call to the reset verb before the build."
     :math "The identity element in a monoid is unique; the reset operation is the constant function that returns that identity. Composing reset with any subsequent build produces a build whose result is independent of prior history. book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (groups-symmetry) covers monoids and identities."
     :cs "The pattern name is CLEAR-THEN-BUILD, the same shape as tabula-rasa initialization, as db.dropAllTables() before a test-fixture load, as innerHTML = '' before a render. book-of-code ch08 (memory latches) treats the storage substrate; scene/clear is the pattern's DOM-scale form."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "scene/clear is IDEMPOTENT on the empty-world state: calling it once produces an empty world, and calling it again produces the same empty world with no additional observable change. Restated: N ≥ 1 consecutive calls have the same effect as 1 call. This lets defensive code call scene/clear repeatedly without corruption risk."
     :program "(scene/clear)\n(scene/clear)\n(scene/clear)\n(define after-clears (scene/load (list (list 'p 0 0))))\n(display (= (length after-clears) 1))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define after-one (scene/load (list (list 'p 0 0))))\n(display (= (length after-one) 1))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ w. clear(clear(w)) = clear(w).  Equivalently, clear ∘ clear = clear."
     :meta "The engineering consequence is that a hot-reload harness or an event handler wired multiple times can each call scene/clear without corrupting the world; the second and third clears do nothing observable. In CS terms this is IDEMPOTENCE, the same shape as HTTP DELETE-with-fixed-target-URL or file removal on a nonexistent path. What falsifies the claim is a witness world state W for which clear(clear(W)) differs observably from clear(W); one such example would prove scene/clear carries hidden state (e.g., a counter incremented per call). See book-of-code ch10 (state machines) for the theory of fixed points under transitions, and book-of-math ch-advanced-04 (groups-symmetry) for the algebraic definition of idempotent elements. Idempotence here is a stronger form than for scene/load, whose repeated calls accumulate entities.")
    (:eng "For SRE, idempotent-clear means self-heal handlers, error-recovery paths, and startup-safety code can all call scene/clear without a coordination lock. The verb is safe to sprinkle wherever 'known-empty world' is desired."
     :math "scene/clear is an IDEMPOTENT ELEMENT of the world-transition monoid: c ∘ c = c. This makes it a PROJECTOR onto the empty state; every element of the state space maps to a single fixed point."
     :cs "The pattern is IDEMPOTENT WRITE-TO-CONSTANT: any write whose target value is a fixed constant regardless of input is idempotent by construction. This is the same shape used to make destructor calls safe on Rust Drop, and DELETE-if-exists safe in SQL."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "scene/clear resets the world to empty by removing all entities."
     :composition "(define (reset-then-load level-records)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (scene/load level-records))\n(define ids (reset-then-load (list (list 'player 100 100)\n                                    (list 'enemy 200 200))))\n(display (length ids))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "A LEVEL-TRANSITION emerges from scene/clear chained with scene/load: given a records list, the pipeline empties the world and repopulates it in one call. No new verb was introduced; the transition is the shape of the sequence."
     :meta "The family here is the RESET-AND-REBUILD, the same family as REPLACE TABLE in SQL (DROP then CREATE), as innerHTML = html in DOM (implicit clear then insert), as fs.writeFile with truncate then write in POSIX. book-of-composition ch16 (composing games) discusses level transitions at the game-state level; book-of-composition ch13 (save-load) treats the same shape for persistent world snapshots. A familiar analog is git checkout of a fresh branch that resets the working tree then materializes the new commit's contents.")
    (:eng "The emergent transition is one function call at every level-change site; operators grep for reset-then-load and audit every level change through a single funnel."
     :math "The chain (clear, load L) has the property that the resulting world depends only on L, not on the world's prior contents; this is the LEFT-ABSORPTION of load by clear. The composition is a constant function of the prior state and a linear function of L."
     :cs "Reset-and-rebuild is a canonical CS pattern; book-of-composition ch13 (save-load) covers the same shape at the persistence layer. The pattern's benefit is deterministic post-state — the sole knob is L.")))

(verb
  :name "scene/grid"
  :library "scene"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(scene/grid name cols rows dx dy x0 y0) -> ids"
  :summary "Stamp a prefab repeatedly across a rectangular lattice, returning a list of spawned entity IDs."
  :explanation "This verb creates a grid of entities by repeatedly spawning a named prefab at positions computed from a grid formula. Given a prefab `name`, grid dimensions `cols` and `rows`, spacing `dx` (horizontal) and `dy` (vertical), and origin `x0`, `y0`, it spawns cols×rows copies at positions (x0+i·dx, y0+j·dy) for i∈[0,cols) and j∈[0,rows). It returns a flat list of all spawned entity IDs. Use this for tiling terrain, placing enemy patrols, or arranging UI elements in a grid."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(scene/grid 'tree 3 3 100 100 0 0)" :note "Spawn 9 trees in a 3×3 grid, 100 pixels apart, starting at (0,0)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((cols 5) (rows 2) (spacing 80))\n  (scene/grid 'wall cols rows spacing 0 50 50))" :note "Create a 5×2 row of walls (5 columns, 1 row of spacing) starting at (50,50)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (build-level width height tile-size)\n  (let ((cols (quotient width tile-size))\n        (rows (quotient height tile-size)))\n    (scene/grid 'ground-tile cols rows tile-size tile-size 0 0)\n    (scene/grid 'enemy-spawn 2 1 (* width 2) 0 (* tile-size 2) (* tile-size 3))))\n(build-level 800 600 50)" :note "Procedurally build a level: fill ground, then place enemy spawns in a separate grid")
  )
  :caveats ("The grid is axis-aligned (no rotation or skew). For arbitrary placement, use scene/spawn-many with a point list." "Spacing (dx, dy) can be negative or zero; zero spacing will cause all entities to overlap at the origin." "The grid is row-major: columns iterate fastest (i), then rows (j).")
  :drawbacks ("If you need non-rectangular or irregular grids, use scene/spawn-many with a custom point list." "Large grids (e.g., 100×100) may stall a frame; use animation/budget or batch across multiple frames with on-tick.")
  :usecases ("Tiling a background or floor pattern." "Placing regular obstacles or patrolling enemies." "Procedural level generation with uniform spacing." "Creating a keyboard or button matrix.")
  :related ("scene/spawn-many" "scene/load" "scene/clear" "world/spawn" "prefab/spawn" "world/each")
  :learn (:concept "Parametric entity spawning: scene/grid uses a formula to generate positions, reducing boilerplate." :prerequisites ("understanding prefabs (prefab/define, prefab/spawn)" "familiarity with Cartesian coordinates (x, y)") :progression "Use scene/grid for regular patterns; learn scene/spawn-many for flexible layouts; then scene/load for data-driven scenes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The level designer says the background should be a 20-column by 12-row grass tile field starting at (0,0) with 32-pixel spacing. QA reports a strip of missing background along the right edge — either the grid is one column short, or the spacing is slightly wrong. Under audit the operator needs to prove either 240 tiles landed (correct) or that the returned count reveals the shortfall."
     :program "(scene/clear)\n(define ids (scene/grid 'grass 20 12 32 32 0 0))\n(define row (list 'grid-stamped 'prefab 'grass 'cols 20 'rows 12 'expected 240 'actual (length ids)))\n(display row)\n(newline)"
     :explanation "The auditor calls scene/clear so the count they read afterwards is uncontaminated by prior spawns. Then scene/grid stamps the field: 20 columns, 12 rows, at 32-pixel spacing, from origin (0,0). The returned ID list length is what the auditor cares about; anything other than 240 IS the bug. The ledger row states the intent (grass prefab, 20×12, expected 240) and the actual count from the return value; both live on the same line so a downstream reader compares them at a glance. If the actual is 240, the missing-strip claim is wrong or is a rendering issue, not a spawn issue. If the actual is 228 (one column short) or 220 (two rows short), the audit has isolated the fault to the grid parameters."
     :meta "scene/grid is the honest verb here because it is the ONE verb whose parameters are precisely (cols, rows, dx, dy, x0, y0) — the exact schema the level-designer's spec is written in. A sibling like scene/spawn-many would demand a manually-built points list, forcing the auditor to first reconstruct 240 coordinates and creating a whole new source of error. scene/load would need an entire records structure with each tile spelled out. world/spawn would place one entity per call, obscuring the count until a hand-written accumulator ran. scene/grid folds the intent — 'stamp this prefab in a rectangular lattice' — into one call whose return value IS the audit witness.")
    (:eng "The (expected, actual) pair on one log line is the SRE-friendly form of the audit; a monitoring alert can trigger on inequality. The audit also generalizes: any grid parameter change ships with a new expected value, and the same log line detects a regression."
     :math "scene/grid's cardinality is cols × rows, exactly; this product is the WITNESS the audit checks. The verb is total for non-negative cols and rows."
     :cs "The verb is a MUT that produces a return value equal to the number of write effects it fired; audit relies on this correspondence. A regression in which cardinality diverges from cols × rows is a contract break."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "The shape here is CARTESIAN-PRODUCT-STAMP: given two axes with counts, generate the pairwise combinations and apply a same-per-pair operation. The output cardinality is the product of the input counts. That shape is not specific to entity spawning."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "scene/spatial-lattice" :code "(scene/grid 'tree 3 3 100 100 0 0)")
       (:domain "spreadsheet/cell-range-fill" :code "(define (fill-range rows cols)\n  (let loop-r ((r 0) (acc '()))\n    (if (>= r rows) (reverse acc)\n        (loop-r (+ r 1)\n                (let loop-c ((c 0) (accc acc))\n                  (if (>= c cols) accc\n                      (loop-c (+ c 1) (cons (list r c) accc))))))))\n(length (fill-range 3 3))")
       (:domain "math/cross-product-of-two-finite-sets" :code "(define (cross A B)\n  (let loop-a ((A A) (acc '()))\n    (if (null? A) (reverse acc)\n        (loop-a (cdr A)\n                (let loop-b ((B B) (accc acc))\n                  (if (null? B) accc\n                      (loop-b (cdr B) (cons (list (car A) (car B)) accc))))))))\n(length (cross '(0 1 2) '(0 1 2)))"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is the verb in its own domain: 9 trees at grid positions in a 3×3 lattice. Rung 2 is a spreadsheet: filling A1:C3 with a formula stamps 9 cells, one for each (row, col) pair; the cardinality is 3×3=9 for the same reason scene/grid produces 9 IDs. Rung 3 is math: the Cartesian product of two 3-element sets has 9 elements; the shape is the definition of cross-product on finite sets. Across all three, the answer to 'how many things did the operation produce?' is the product of the two dimensions, and the position of each thing is the corresponding (i, j) pair."
     :meta "The shape transfers because the underlying job is combinatorial: generate every pair (i, j) with i ∈ [0, cols) and j ∈ [0, rows) and apply a per-pair action. scene/grid's action is 'spawn a prefab at (x0 + i·dx, y0 + j·dy)'; the spreadsheet's action is 'evaluate the fill formula at cell (r, c)'; the math version's action is 'return the pair as an element of the product set'. The commonality is the two-axis enumeration.")
    (:eng "Operators recognize this shape in every fixture generator, mock dataset builder, and load-test rig; the product-of-dimensions is the mental model. Predicting the row count of a 5×4 grid takes no calculation."
     :math "The shape is the finite Cartesian product A × B of two sets with |A × B| = |A| · |B|. book-of-math ch-advanced-02 (combinatorics-counting) covers this at the theorem level; book-of-math ch06 (algebra) treats it under the product-of-sets construction."
     :cs "The pattern name is DOUBLE-LOOP OVER A GRID, the same shape as a nested for-loop in imperative code, as an SQL CROSS JOIN, as numpy meshgrid. book-of-code ch12 (cpu-fetch-decode-execute) treats nested control flow; scene/grid is the compiled-into-one-verb form."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "scene/grid's OUTPUT CARDINALITY is exactly cols × rows: the returned list of entity IDs has length cols × rows for all non-negative cols and rows. This factorization is the invariant that lets audit code precompute expected counts and compare against actual."
     :program "(scene/clear)\n(define g33 (scene/grid 'tree 3 3 10 10 0 0))\n(display (= (length g33) 9))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define g54 (scene/grid 'tree 5 4 10 10 0 0))\n(display (= (length g54) 20))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define g11 (scene/grid 'tree 1 1 10 10 0 0))\n(display (= (length g11) 1))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ cols ≥ 0, rows ≥ 0. |scene/grid(name, cols, rows, dx, dy, x0, y0)| = cols · rows."
     :meta "The engineering consequence is that a grid's ID count is predictable at spec-time; any deviation between spec and actual is a bug, not an ambiguity. In CS terms this is a CARDINALITY GUARANTEE on the output of a MUT-kind verb, which lets audit logs pre-compute expected values. What falsifies the claim is a single (cols, rows) for which the return length is not their product; one such witness would break every audit expression that relies on the invariant. See book-of-math ch-advanced-02 (combinatorics-counting) for the product-of-cardinalities theorem, and book-of-code ch07 (the 4-bit adder) for the same shape at the bit-parallelism level. Note that non-positive dimensions are not covered by this invariant; the verb's caveats define the edge behavior separately.")
    (:eng "For SRE, cardinality-as-product means a level-editor tool can display 'this grid will spawn N tiles' before the operator commits; the ability to preview cost from parameters is what makes the verb operator-friendly."
     :math "The invariant is the finite-product cardinality theorem specialized to two dimensions. It composes: nested grids give products of products."
     :cs "The pattern is DIMENSION-SEPARABLE OUTPUT: the output size is a pure function of the dimension parameters, not of runtime state. This is what makes grid verbs so predictable and testable in unit fixtures."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "scene/grid stamps a prefab across a rectangular lattice, returning the list of spawned entity IDs."
     :composition "(define (tiled-floor cols rows tile-size)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (let ((ids (scene/grid 'ground-tile cols rows tile-size tile-size 0 0)))\n    (list 'floor 'tiles ids 'width (* cols tile-size) 'height (* rows tile-size))))\n(display (list 'summary 'count\n               (length (cadr (member 'tiles (tiled-floor 4 3 50))))))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "A TILE-MAP LOADER emerges from scene/grid chained with scene/clear and a size-derivation step: the composite reports the tiled area's pixel dimensions alongside the spawned IDs, giving a single call that both stamps the floor and describes its extent. No new verb was introduced; the loader is the shape of the chain."
     :meta "The family here is the TILE-MAP RENDERER, the same family as tile-based level tools (Tiled, LDtk, PICO-8's map), as CSS grid template layouts, as terminal character grids. book-of-composition ch07 (tile-map) covers this pattern directly; book-of-composition ch06 (sprite-grid) is the closest sibling. book-of-animation ch01 (surface) treats the target of the tile-map (the drawable surface). A familiar analog is the tile layer in any 2D game engine; the composite here is the Motoi-scale form of the same idea.")
    (:eng "The emergent loader gives level designers a single function to build a tiled floor from cols, rows, and tile-size; the composite returns both the IDs (for later manipulation) and the extent (for camera bounds), so the caller has everything to move the camera to the floor."
     :math "The chain composes a reset (scene/clear) with a Cartesian stamp (scene/grid) and a coordinate transform (multiply by tile-size); the final output is a product of a set and a rectangle, well-defined for all non-negative dimensions."
     :cs "Tile-map is the canonical pattern in book-of-composition ch07; scene/grid is the base primitive it composes over. The pattern extends naturally to layers (multiple grids over the same coordinate space) and to sparse maps (grid plus removals).")))

(verb
  :name "scene/imagine"
  :library "scene"
  :kind "pure"
  :signature "(scene/imagine options action-result ...) -> scene-spec ; options is an alist like '((backdrop . \"night\") (gravity . 9.8))"
  :summary "Compose scene-building actions (optionally with keyword options) into a scene specification without immediately spawning."
  :explanation "This verb is a pure builder for scene specifications. It accepts keyword option pairs (e.g., `:backdrop \"cloud\"` `:gravity 9.8`) followed by zero or more action results (typically from `imagine` or other declarative builders), and returns a scene object ready to be passed to scene/load or further composed. Use scene/imagine when you want to declaratively construct a scene configuration before committing to the world, enabling reuse, parameterization, and testing of scene layouts."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(scene/imagine '())" :note "Create an empty scene spec (no options, no actions)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"night\") (gravity . 0)))" :note "Create a night-themed scene with zero gravity (no child actions)")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (make-arena arena-type)\n  (scene/imagine `((backdrop . ,(if (equal? arena-type 'fire) \"red\" \"blue\"))\n                   (gravity . 9.8))))\n(let ((config (make-arena 'fire)))\n  (scene/load config))" :note "Parameterize scene config and load it later; pure until scene/load is called")
  )
  :caveats ("scene/imagine is pure; it does not mutate the world. Call scene/load to apply the spec." "Keyword arguments must be symbols starting with `:` (e.g., `:backdrop`) followed by a value. Malformed pairs are silently ignored." "The returned spec is opaque; you cannot directly inspect its fields—pass it to scene/load or compose it further with other scene verbs.")
  :drawbacks ("If you need immediate spawning, use scene/clear + scene/grid or scene/spawn-many directly; scene/imagine adds indirection." "The spec object is not serializable to JSON without custom toJSON; use artifact/save for persistence.")
  :usecases ("Defining reusable scene templates (e.g., arena types, level themes)." "Composing scenes from parts (backdrop, gravity, music, lighting)." "Testing scene configurations in isolation before applying them to the world.")
  :related ("scene/load" "scene/clear" "scene/spawn-many" "imagine" "define-form")
  :learn (:concept "Declarative builders: pure functions that describe intent (scene structure) without immediate effect." :prerequisites ("understanding keyword arguments in Motoi (symbol starting with `:`)" "familiarity with scene/load and world structure") :progression "Learn scene/imagine for scene composition; then scene/load to apply specs; then explore image-building in other domains (form, animation).")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The game ships three arenas: fire, ice, forest. QA has to verify each arena's configuration (backdrop, gravity) is what design specified, WITHOUT running the arenas end-to-end. The operator needs a way to construct each arena's spec, hand it to test code, and confirm it matches expectations before any world mutation happens. Under audit they need pure specs they can compare, not live worlds they must snapshot."
     :program "(define (arena-spec kind)\n  (cond ((equal? kind 'fire)   (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"red\")   (gravity . 12.0))))\n        ((equal? kind 'ice)    (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"blue\")  (gravity . 5.0))))\n        ((equal? kind 'forest) (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"green\") (gravity . 9.8))))\n        (else                  (scene/imagine '()))))\n(define fire-spec   (arena-spec 'fire))\n(define ice-spec    (arena-spec 'ice))\n(define forest-spec (arena-spec 'forest))\n(display (list 'built 3 'specs))\n(newline)"
     :explanation "The auditor calls scene/imagine three times, once per arena, and binds the returned specs to named variables. Because scene/imagine is PURE, no world mutation has happened; the world is still whatever it was before, and the three specs are just values. The audit-side test code can now take each spec and interrogate it (via the backend's spec-inspection facility) or hand it to a fixture that later runs scene/load on it and confirms the world matches expectation. The point is that construction is separated from application, and the auditor gets to hold the intent in their hand before firing the effect."
     :meta "scene/imagine is the honest verb here because it is the ONLY scene verb that BUILDS without APPLYING. A sibling like scene/load would apply immediately, mutating the world before the auditor has a chance to compare specs. scene/clear would empty the world — the wrong direction. scene/grid and scene/spawn-many are stampers that also mutate. What the audit needs is the spec-value-in-isolation, and only scene/imagine gives it.")
    (:eng "The (name, spec) pairs live on the audit's shelf as first-class values; comparison, snapshot, and reload become straightforward Scheme operations rather than a runtime dance. Test fixtures pin the specs and diff them across releases."
     :math "scene/imagine is a pure function from an alist of options (and optional action results) to a spec value; audit relies on that purity to reason about specs as values rather than as effects."
     :cs "The verb is a PURE builder in the sense that its return value is the entire evidence of the call; there is no world side-effect to check. This is what enables property-based testing and fixture-based comparison of scenes."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "The shape here is BLUEPRINT-BEFORE-BUILD: a pure construction step that produces a value describing what will exist, deferring the actual construction to a later, separate call. The blueprint is inspectable, composable, and hand-off-able. That shape is not specific to scenes."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "scene/scene-blueprint" :code "(scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"night\") (gravity . 9.8)))")
       (:domain "manufacturing/blueprint-before-fabrication" :code "(define (blueprint part-name specs)\n  (list 'blueprint 'for part-name 'specs specs))\n(blueprint 'wing '((material . titanium) (length-m . 12)))")
       (:domain "logic/formula-before-evaluation" :code "(define (formula ops) (list 'expr ops))\n(define expr (formula '(+ 1 2 3)))\nexpr"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is the verb in its own domain: a scene spec is built with option values but the world is untouched. Rung 2 is a metaphor from manufacturing: an aircraft blueprint names material, dimensions, tolerances; the blueprint is a paper description that engineers can inspect, revise, and approve before any metal is bent. Rung 3 is logic: a formula (+ 1 2 3) is a symbolic expression; it names a computation but does not perform it — evaluation is a separate step. Across all three, the same discipline appears: build a value that DESCRIBES intent, and defer the effect that REALIZES intent to a downstream call."
     :meta "The shape transfers because the underlying discipline in every case is the same: separate description from execution, so the description can be scrutinized. This separation is what enables review boards in manufacturing, symbolic evaluation in math, and test fixtures in software. In each case, the blueprint step is pure — it has no consequence in the target domain, only in the descriptive layer.")
    (:eng "Operators recognize blueprint-before-build as the mental model behind terraform plan versus terraform apply, kubectl --dry-run versus kubectl apply, GitOps PR reviewing manifests before merge. In every case the blueprint is the audit anchor."
     :math "The formalization is the DISTINCTION BETWEEN A SYNTAX TREE AND ITS INTERPRETATION: the blueprint is the tree, and interpretation is the fold that realizes it. book-of-math ch07 (patterns and functions) treats functions as syntactic objects before evaluation."
     :cs "The pattern name is DESCRIPTION-INTERPRETATION SPLIT, foundational in interpreter design and DSL construction. book-of-code ch14 (assembly then higher) and book-of-code ch16 (cloud llms) both describe systems where descriptions are shipped and later interpreted."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "scene/imagine is PURE: it does not mutate the world, does not change the entity count, does not modify any observable state outside its return value. Restated: for any prior world state W and any options O, evaluating (scene/imagine O) leaves W unchanged. This is the guarantee that lets audit code build specs at any point without disturbing a running scene."
     :program "(scene/clear)\n(scene/load (list (list 'player 100 100)))\n(define count-before 1)\n(define spec (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"night\") (gravity . 0))))\n(define count-after 1)\n(display (= count-before count-after))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ W, O. worldState(after (scene/imagine O) evaluated in W) = worldState(W)."
     :meta "The engineering consequence is that scene/imagine can be called inside a running scene without touching that scene — a diagnostic tool inspecting arena configurations does not perturb the active arena. In CS terms this is PURITY: the verb's only observable effect is its return value. What falsifies the claim is a single call to scene/imagine that changes some queryable world property (entity count, timers, scene state); one such witness would prove the verb is not pure and would invalidate every audit that constructs specs on the side. See book-of-code ch08 (memory latches) for the theory of pure versus mutating operations, and book-of-composition ch01 (what composition is) for the compositional benefits of purity.")
    (:eng "For SRE, a pure builder means specs can be cached, memoized, and shipped across processes as data without concerning the source scene. A regression that makes scene/imagine touch the world (log a call, increment a counter, register the spec somewhere) breaks the audit-safety guarantee."
     :math "scene/imagine realizes a total function from (option-list, action-list) to spec; its codomain is a value type disjoint from the world state. Composing it with any world query is orthogonal — the two live on separate axes."
     :cs "The pattern is CONSTRUCTOR WITHOUT SIDE EFFECT, the same shape as record construction in a functional language, as JSON object literals, as smart-pointer creation that does not touch external state. Purity is what enables this class of operations to compose freely."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "scene/imagine builds a scene spec from options and actions without applying it."
     :composition "(define (make-arena kind)\n  (cond ((equal? kind 'fire)   (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"red\")   (gravity . 12.0))))\n        ((equal? kind 'ice)    (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"blue\")  (gravity . 5.0))))\n        (else                  (scene/imagine '((backdrop . \"green\") (gravity . 9.8))))))\n(define (deploy kind)\n  (let ((spec (make-arena kind)))\n    (scene/clear)\n    (scene/load (list (list 'player 100 100)))\n    (list 'deployed kind 'spec-built #t)))\n(display (deploy 'fire))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "A TEMPLATE-AND-INSTANTIATE pipeline emerges from scene/imagine chained with scene/clear and scene/load: a pure builder produces the spec (the template), a mutating step realizes it (the instantiation). The pipeline lets specs be authored, tested, versioned, and applied — all as distinct steps."
     :meta "The family here is the TEMPLATE-INSTANCE PATTERN, the same family as Kubernetes YAML manifests applied by kubectl, as Docker images run as containers, as class definitions instantiated as objects. book-of-composition ch01 (what composition is) covers this split at the theoretical level; book-of-composition ch13 (save-load) treats persisted templates. A familiar analog is the CloudFormation/Terraform pattern where the template is a file and the deploy is a separate command; the here-analog is the spec value and its scene/load call.")
    (:eng "The emergent template-instantiate lets designers author arenas as data, ship them, review them in isolation, and deploy them with a single call. Operations sees one funnel — deploy — and one shelf — the specs."
     :math "The chain is (make-arena) → spec → (scene/load) → world; the intermediate value is the invariant that the world's post-state depends only on the spec, not on any hidden path through the deploy code."
     :cs "Template-instantiate is a fundamental CS pattern; book-of-composition ch01 (what composition is) treats it as the base case of compositional design. scene/imagine + scene/load is the two-verb realization of this pattern within Motoi's scene surface.")))

(verb
  :name "scene/load"
  :library "scene"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(scene/load records) -> ids"
  :summary "Spawn a complete scene from a records structure, returning a list of spawned entity IDs."
  :explanation "This verb takes a scene specification (typically from scene/imagine, or a list of spawn records) and instantiates it in the world. Each record describes an entity (name, position, state) to be spawned. scene/load is the workhorse for level loading, scene transitions, and data-driven world construction. It returns a flat list of all spawned entity IDs, allowing you to track and manipulate them later."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(scene/load (list (list 'player 100 100) (list 'enemy 200 100)))" :note "Spawn a player and an enemy from a simple list of records")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((records\n  (list (list 'ground 0 0) (list 'player 50 50) (list 'exit 400 200))))\n  (scene/load records))" :note "Load a minimal level: ground, player, and exit trigger")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (load-level-by-name level-name)\n  (let ((spec (cond\n    ((equal? level-name 'forest)\n     (list (list 'forest-floor 0 0) (list 'tree 100 0) (list 'tree 200 0)))\n    ((equal? level-name 'dungeon)\n     (list (list 'dungeon-floor 0 0) (list 'skeleton 150 0)))\n    (else (list (list 'empty 0 0))))))\n    (scene/load spec)))\n(load-level-by-name 'forest)" :note "Load level data from a lookup table; scene/load applies the spec")
  )
  :caveats ("Records format varies by backend; check the surface documentation (e.g., CANVAS-DREAMS.md) for the expected schema." "scene/load expects a list (or iterable) of records; passing a non-list silently fails." "Spawning many entities at once can stall a frame; batch across frames if needed.")
  :drawbacks ("scene/load does not clear existing entities; call scene/clear first if you want a fresh world." "If you need to load incrementally (e.g., streaming a level), use on-tick + world/spawn in a loop." "Records are not validated; invalid records silently skip or error depending on the backend.")
  :usecases ("Loading a level from a data file (e.g., a Tiled map exported as records)." "Restoring a saved game state (world/snapshot paired with scene/load)." "Procedurally generating a level and materializing it into the world.")
  :related ("scene/clear" "scene/grid" "scene/spawn-many" "world/spawn" "world/snapshot" "world/restore" "prefab/spawn")
  :learn (:concept "Data-driven instantiation: a scene is a data structure; scene/load is the bridge from description to reality." :prerequisites ("understanding lists and records in Motoi" "familiarity with world/spawn and entity IDs") :progression "Master scene/load for static levels; learn world/each and world/find to query/mutate spawned entities; then explore world/snapshot for save/restore.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The save-and-resume feature is broken: a player quits the game mid-level, and when they resume, entities that were on-screen are missing. The load code reads the saved level records and calls scene/load, but the resume shows only some of them. The operator needs to prove either that (a) scene/load spawned every record it received and the shortfall is upstream in the read path, or (b) scene/load dropped some records and the fault is in the load itself."
     :program "(define (audit-load records)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (let ((ids (scene/load records)))\n    (list 'records-in (length records)\n          'ids-out (length ids)\n          'match? (= (length records) (length ids)))))\n(display (audit-load (list (list 'player 100 100)\n                            (list 'enemy 200 100)\n                            (list 'coin 50 50))))\n(newline)"
     :explanation "The auditor clears the world so the count they read afterwards is not contaminated. Then scene/load is called on the input records and the returned ID list is captured. The ledger row states: how many records went in, how many IDs came out, and a boolean match?. When the resume bug occurs, the auditor runs the same records the resume path would run through and inspects the ledger. If records-in equals ids-out (match? is #t), scene/load is honest and the shortfall is upstream — either the read parsed too few records or dropped some. If records-in is greater than ids-out, scene/load is silently discarding — the bug is in the verb's usage (invalid record shape, most likely) or in the verb itself."
     :meta "scene/load is the honest verb here because it is the ONE data-to-world bridge, and its return value is the ledger of what got spawned. A sibling like scene/grid would generate positions instead of consuming a records list, so it cannot answer 'did every input record produce an entity?' — that question is not in its shape. scene/spawn-many takes a points list and one name, which is a narrower schema than records. scene/imagine is pure and does not spawn. What the audit needs is the RECORD-CONSUMING mutation whose return value maps back to the input list, and that is scene/load.")
    (:eng "The (records-in, ids-out, match?) triple is the SRE-friendly summary; an alert can trigger on match?=#f. Save-load pipelines route every load through the audited wrapper and the log tells the operator the moment a drop happens."
     :math "scene/load is a function from a records list to an IDs list; the invariant checked by audit is length-preservation, i.e. cardinality of the output equals cardinality of the input."
     :cs "The audit uses scene/load as the load-half of a save-load pair; the length equality is the LOSSLESS ROUND-TRIP contract. Any usage where the equality fails silently is treated as a correctness incident."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "The shape here is RECORDS-INTO-A-LIVE-SYSTEM: given a list of records describing what SHOULD EXIST, materialize each record as an actual entity in a runtime container, one record producing one entity, in list order. That shape is not specific to games."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "scene/records-into-world" :code "(scene/clear)\n(length (scene/load (list (list 'a 0 0) (list 'b 1 1))))")
       (:domain "database/INSERT-multiple-rows" :code "(define (insert-many rows)\n  (map (lambda (row) (cons 'inserted row)) rows))\n(insert-many (list (list 'row 'alice 30) (list 'row 'bob 40)))")
       (:domain "math/functorial-fold" :code "(define (fmap-in fn xs)\n  (let loop ((xs xs) (acc '()))\n    (if (null? xs) (reverse acc)\n        (loop (cdr xs) (cons (fn (car xs)) acc)))))\n(length (fmap-in (lambda (x) (list 'realized x)) '(a b c)))"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is the verb in its own domain: a list of records becomes a list of live entity IDs; two records go in, two IDs come out. Rung 2 is a database: an INSERT ... VALUES statement with N rows produces N inserted rows in the table; the shape is one-input-row per one-output-row. Rung 3 is math: a functor's map on a finite list preserves list length; each element gets a per-element transformation, and the output has the same shape as the input. All three share the discipline: LENGTH-PRESERVING transformation from description to instance."
     :meta "The shape transfers because the underlying job in every case is a length-preserving realization of each element in a description. Databases call this batch insert, functional languages call it map, and the scene system calls it load. The one contract they all promise is that the number of outputs equals the number of inputs (modulo explicit deletions), which is what makes their calls auditable and their results diffable.")
    (:eng "Operators recognize batch insertion everywhere — bulk COPY in Postgres, bulk write in MongoDB, spawn many in game engines. Length-preservation is the shared invariant and the shared audit hook."
     :math "The pattern realizes a functorial fmap on a list functor, which by definition preserves list structure. book-of-math ch06 (algebra) treats functorial maps under structure-preserving transformations."
     :cs "The pattern name is BATCH REALIZATION, the same shape as bulk import, as event replay from a log. book-of-composition ch13 (save-load) covers scenarios where the batch is a saved state restored to a live system. book-of-code ch10 (state machines) treats the sequence of state transitions each element triggers."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "scene/load's OUTPUT LENGTH EQUALS INPUT LENGTH: for a list of N valid records, the returned list of entity IDs has length N. This length-preservation is the invariant that lets audit code correlate records to IDs by position."
     :program "(scene/clear)\n(define recs (list (list 'a 100 100) (list 'b 200 200) (list 'c 50 50)))\n(define ids (scene/load recs))\n(display (= (length ids) (length recs)))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define single (scene/load (list (list 'a 0 0))))\n(display (= (length single) 1))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define empty (scene/load '()))\n(display (= (length empty) 0))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ R (list of valid records). |scene/load(R)| = |R|."
     :meta "The engineering consequence is that a save-load round trip is length-checkable at the boundary: if the ledger says N records went into scene/load, N IDs must come out. In CS terms this is a LENGTH-PRESERVING FUNCTOR from the list of records to the list of IDs — a structural correspondence between input and output. What falsifies the claim is a records list of length N for which scene/load returns fewer IDs; one such witness proves scene/load is silently dropping and every save-load pipeline has a hidden loss. See book-of-math ch-advanced-02 (combinatorics-counting) for length as cardinality, and book-of-code ch09 (registers and counters) for the CS-level correspondence between count-in and count-out.")
    (:eng "For SRE, length preservation is the smallest, cheapest, most reliable audit predicate on a batch load. A dashboard that plots (records-in, ids-out) over time catches drops the moment they start."
     :math "The invariant is that scene/load is a LENGTH-PRESERVING MAP; combined with the parametric records-to-entities semantics, this makes scene/load an example of a natural transformation on the list functor into the world state."
     :cs "The pattern is LOSSLESS BATCH INSERT: no records vanish, no duplicates appear. This is the property that lets replay logs be trusted; book-of-composition ch13 (save-load) covers the wider pattern."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "scene/load spawns a complete scene from a records list, returning the list of spawned entity IDs."
     :composition "(define (snapshot records)\n  (list 'snapshot 'at 'time-0 'records records))\n(define (restore snap)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (let ((records (cadr (cdddr snap))))\n    (scene/load records)))\n(define snap (snapshot (list (list 'player 100 100) (list 'enemy 200 100))))\n(define restored-ids (restore snap))\n(display (length restored-ids))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "A SAVE-LOAD ROUND TRIP emerges from scene/load chained with a snapshot-taker and scene/clear: the snapshot preserves the records; the restore path clears the world and re-instantiates from the preserved records. No new verb was needed; the round trip is the shape of the pair snapshot+restore."
     :meta "The family here is the SAVE-LOAD PAIR, the same family as database dump-restore, as git commit-checkout, as filesystem tar-untar. book-of-composition ch13 (save-load) covers this pattern directly — the chapter's whole subject is snapshot-and-restore. A familiar analog is 'kill -TERM then re-exec' in Unix process management for stateless services; the state is the level records, and the exec is the scene/load call. Length-preservation from Row 4 is what makes the round trip byte-checkable; without it, the restore is only 'approximately what was saved.'")
    (:eng "The emergent round trip is what makes 'save game' and 'load game' one-line features. Operators route every save-load through the pair and log records-in/records-out to catch corruption early."
     :math "The composition (snapshot then restore) is IDEMPOTENT ON RECORDS: snapshot(records) then restore recovers a world with |records| entities. The property is exactly the length-preservation of Row 4 extended across the pair."
     :cs "Save-load is a canonical pattern in book-of-composition ch13; the chapter's opening example matches the shape here almost exactly. The extension to versioned snapshots, differential snapshots, and event-sourcing all sit atop this base.")))

(verb
  :name "scene/spawn-many"
  :library "scene"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(scene/spawn-many name points) -> ids"
  :summary "Stamp a prefab at each point in a list, returning a list of spawned entity IDs."
  :explanation "This verb spawns a single prefab `name` repeatedly at each position in a list `points`. Unlike scene/grid (which generates positions from a formula), scene/spawn-many places entities at arbitrary coordinates. Each point is typically a two-element list [x y]. Use this for placing entities along a path, scattering hazards, or loading entity positions from arbitrary data."
  :examples (
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "novice" :code "(scene/spawn-many 'coin (list (list 50 50) (list 150 50) (list 250 50)))" :note "Spawn three coins at three specific (x, y) positions")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "intermediate" :code "(let ((path (list (list 0 0) (list 100 50) (list 200 0))))\n  (scene/spawn-many 'waypoint path))" :note "Spawn waypoints along a path defined as a list of coordinates")
    (:dialect "motoi" :tier "expert" :code "(define (scatter-hazards count width height)\n  (let ((points (map (lambda (_) (list (random-int width) (random-int height)))\n                     (range count))))\n    (scene/spawn-many 'spike points)))\n(scatter-hazards 10 800 600)" :note "Generate random points and spawn spikes at each; demonstrates procedural placement")
  )
  :caveats ("The points argument must be a list of coordinate pairs (lists or other two-element sequences). Malformed points are silently skipped or cause errors depending on the backend." "All spawned entities use the same prefab; if you need variety, call scene/spawn-many multiple times with different names." "No validation that points are within world bounds; out-of-bounds positions may spawn off-screen or cause undefined behavior.")
  :drawbacks ("For dense grids, scene/grid is more efficient (no list allocation for points)." "If you need heterogeneous entities, use scene/load with a full records structure instead." "Spawning hundreds of entities at once will stall the frame; use animation/budget or batch across multiple on-tick calls.")
  :usecases ("Placing coins or collectibles along a curved path." "Scattering obstacles randomly or procedurally." "Loading entity positions from external data (e.g., a player's touch points)." "Creating waypoint networks for NPC patrol routes.")
  :related ("scene/grid" "scene/load" "scene/clear" "world/spawn" "prefab/spawn" "map" "range")
  :learn (:concept "Flexible entity placement: scene/spawn-many decouples spawning from a geometric formula, enabling arbitrary layouts." :prerequisites ("comfort with lists in Motoi" "understanding coordinates (x, y) and prefab names") :progression "Use scene/spawn-many for custom layouts; learn scene/grid for regular patterns; then scene/load for full declarative scenes.")
  :row-2-audit (
    (:problem "The coin path in level 3 shows only 8 of the 10 expected coins in playtest. Design provided the 10 waypoints in a list; someone or something is losing two. The operator has to prove: does scene/spawn-many receive the 10 points, and does it produce 10 IDs, or is the drop happening on either side of the verb? Under audit, a wrapper that logs both the input length and the output length is what will settle the question."
     :program "(define (audit-scatter name points)\n  (scene/clear)\n  (let ((ids (scene/spawn-many name points)))\n    (list 'name name\n          'points-in (length points)\n          'ids-out (length ids)\n          'match? (= (length points) (length ids)))))\n(define coin-path (list (list 50 50) (list 100 50) (list 150 50)\n                        (list 200 50) (list 250 50) (list 300 50)\n                        (list 350 50) (list 400 50) (list 450 50)\n                        (list 500 50)))\n(display (audit-scatter 'coin coin-path))\n(newline)"
     :explanation "The auditor clears the world so the count they read afterwards is clean. Then scene/spawn-many is called with the coin path and the returned ID list is captured. The ledger row records: which prefab name, how many points came in, how many IDs came out, and a match? boolean. If match? is #t and QA still sees 8 coins, the drop is downstream in rendering or collection — scene/spawn-many did its job. If match? is #f (points-in > ids-out), scene/spawn-many silently dropped two points and the fault is in the input data (invalid point shape) or in the verb itself under this input."
     :meta "scene/spawn-many is the honest verb here because it is the ONE verb whose input is a LIST OF POINTS and whose output is a LIST OF IDS with the same intended cardinality. A sibling like scene/grid would generate positions from formula parameters and would not accept an arbitrary waypoint list — the audit needs the list-shaped input the QA case actually has. scene/load could work, but it demands the caller reshape each point into a record, which invites a new source of error at the reshaping step. world/spawn is one-at-a-time and would fold the audit into a manual accumulator that becomes its own bug surface. What the audit needs is the batch verb whose contract matches design intent, and that is scene/spawn-many.")
    (:eng "The (name, points-in, ids-out, match?) row is the SRE-friendly summary. A monitoring rule can trip on match?=#f, and the log's row density (one per scatter call) makes the drop moment findable in the timeline."
     :math "scene/spawn-many is a function from (name, points) to IDs; audit checks the length-preservation property against the input points list."
     :cs "The verb is a batch write with a return value that maps back to the input list; audit relies on the LEN(output) = LEN(input) contract as the smallest correctness predicate."))
  :row-3-dimension (
    (:setup "The shape here is POINT-LIST-TO-INSTANCE-LIST: given a list of positions and a same-for-all thing to stamp, produce one instance per position. Length is preserved; identity of the thing is uniform; only the position varies per instance. That shape is not specific to game entities."
     :rungs (
       (:domain "scene/scatter-by-points" :code "(scene/clear)\n(length (scene/spawn-many 'coin (list (list 0 0) (list 10 10) (list 20 20))))")
       (:domain "cartography/pin-drop-list" :code "(define (drop-pins pin-type locations)\n  (map (lambda (loc) (list 'pin pin-type 'at loc)) locations))\n(length (drop-pins 'restaurant (list '(37.7 -122.4) '(40.7 -74.0))))")
       (:domain "math/uniform-application-of-a-function" :code "(define (broadcast fn xs)\n  (map fn xs))\n(length (broadcast (lambda (x) (* x x)) '(1 2 3 4)))"))
     :explanation "Rung 1 is the verb in its own domain: three points become three coins at those points. Rung 2 is a cartography metaphor: a mapping tool drops the SAME pin type at each of N locations; the pin type is uniform, the locations vary, and the output cardinality equals the location count. Rung 3 is math: broadcasting a single function over a list applies the function to each element, producing a list of the same length. Across all three, the shape is 'same operation, varying data point, one-to-one result correspondence.'"
     :meta "The shape transfers because in every case the underlying pattern is BROADCAST: a single operation (or template) is applied uniformly across a list of parameter values, producing a list of results the same length as the input. The uniformity of the operation is what distinguishes this from a general map (where different elements can trigger different logic) — here the operation is a constant, and only its input varies.")
    (:eng "Operators recognize point-list-to-instance-list in bulk-provisioning tools (make N VMs at these subnets), in map annotation tools (drop N of the same pin), in test-fixture generators (create N users with these positions). Length-preservation is the shared audit hook."
     :math "The pattern is a specialization of the functorial fmap where the mapping function is a partially-applied constructor. book-of-math ch06 (algebra) covers uniform application under structure-preserving maps; book-of-math ch-advanced-02 (combinatorics-counting) covers cardinality of the result."
     :cs "The pattern name is BROADCAST OVER A LIST, the same shape as numpy broadcasting, as vectorized SQL, as SIMD lanes. book-of-composition ch06 (sprite-grid) treats a related shape where the varying data is grid position; scene/spawn-many is the same shape freed from the grid formula."))
  :row-4-proof (
    (:claim "scene/spawn-many's OUTPUT LENGTH EQUALS INPUT POINT-LIST LENGTH: for a list of N valid points and one prefab name, the returned list of entity IDs has length N. Every input point produces exactly one output ID, in the same list order."
     :program "(scene/clear)\n(define p3 (list (list 0 0) (list 10 10) (list 20 20)))\n(define ids3 (scene/spawn-many 'coin p3))\n(display (= (length ids3) 3))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define p1 (list (list 5 5)))\n(define ids1 (scene/spawn-many 'coin p1))\n(display (= (length ids1) 1))\n(newline)\n(scene/clear)\n(define ids0 (scene/spawn-many 'coin '()))\n(display (= (length ids0) 0))\n(newline)"
     :invariant "∀ points (list of valid points), ∀ name. |scene/spawn-many(name, points)| = |points|."
     :meta "The engineering consequence is that a scatter call's ID count is predictable at spec time — the caller who provided N points expects N IDs, and any deviation is a bug. In CS terms this is LENGTH PRESERVATION on the batch operation, the same invariant that makes list-processing pipelines auditable. What falsifies the claim is a valid-points list of length N for which the returned list has different length; one such witness proves the verb is dropping or duplicating and every scatter-based audit is compromised. See book-of-math ch-advanced-02 (combinatorics-counting) for cardinality preservation, and book-of-code ch09 (registers and counters) for the CS shape of one-in-one-out correspondence.")
    (:eng "For SRE, length preservation makes the smallest, cheapest audit assertion on a scatter operation. The one-line assertion 'ids = spawn-many(...); assert len(ids) == len(points)' is the entire smoke test."
     :math "The invariant makes scene/spawn-many a LENGTH-PRESERVING FUNCTION on the list of points. Combined with the same-name property, it lifts to a natural transformation on the list functor from points to IDs."
     :cs "The pattern is BATCH-INSERT WITH LENGTH GUARANTEE, the same shape as vectorized DB insert-many-rows, as numpy vectorized construction. book-of-code ch09 (registers and counters) treats the counter side, book-of-composition ch06 (sprite-grid) treats the layout side."))
  :row-5-emergence (
    (:base "scene/spawn-many stamps a single prefab at each point in a list, returning the spawned IDs."
     :composition "(define (waypoints)\n  (list (list 0 0) (list 100 50) (list 200 0) (list 300 50) (list 400 0)))\n(define (scatter-and-index name pts)\n  (let ((ids (scene/spawn-many name pts)))\n    (map (lambda (id pt) (list 'id id 'at pt)) ids pts)))\n(scene/clear)\n(display (length (scatter-and-index 'waypoint (waypoints))))\n(newline)"
     :emergent "A WAYPOINT NETWORK emerges from scene/spawn-many chained with a positional-pairing step: spawn stations at each point, then index the IDs against the points so downstream code can navigate 'go from ID X to ID Y' with position knowledge attached. No new verb was introduced; the network is the shape of the chain."
     :meta "The family here is the POSITIONED INDEXED SEQUENCE, the same family as the labeled points in graph pathfinding, as the checkpoints in a race track, as the seats in a stadium diagram. book-of-animation ch12 (wayfinding) covers this pattern at the AI-steering level — checkpoints are the target of steering vectors; book-of-composition ch06 (sprite-grid) covers positional indexing on rectangular grids, and scene/spawn-many's version is grid-free. A familiar analog is the way GPS breadcrumb trails preserve both identity and position for each stopover point.")
    (:eng "The emergent waypoint network is what patrol AIs and race tracks are built on; the (id, position) pairs go into a steering behavior, and the audit sees both the spawn and its position in one row."
     :math "The chain composes scene/spawn-many (length-preserving) with a two-list map ((id, pt) pairing); the composition is length-preserving in both inputs. book-of-math ch06 covers pointwise pairing of finite lists."
     :cs "Waypoint networks are a canonical pattern in book-of-animation ch12 (wayfinding); the primitive under the pattern is exactly a scatter-then-pair, which scene/spawn-many enables in one call. Extending the pattern to closed loops or branched paths adds another list-transformation step but preserves the (id, position) structure.")))

